				<coordinates>35.2296002,31.7784813,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="0E638D43873F2C099A68">
			<name>Acre</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<bettercanvas-portal style="overflow: visible; position: relative; width: 0px; height: 0px; display: block;"></bettercanvas-portal><div>After the end of a papal interregnum and Pope Gregory X's election in 1271, the Polo's meet him in Acre after returning by ship from Ayas (Marco Polo and R. E. Latham, <i>The Travels of Marco Polo</i>, Repr, Penguin Classics (Harmondsworth [etc.]: Penguin, 1978), 37.).<br></div><div><br></div><div>Link Paiza to here, the relative start of the journey eastward, where it would be needed to pass safely through Mongol territory.<br></div><div><br></div><div>&nbsp;<i>English:&nbsp; Paiza Found in the Former Lands of the Golden Horde (Dniepr River, 1845)</i>. 13th centurydate QS:P,+ - -00T00:00:00Z/7 1250. E.D.Phillips-The Mongols. <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Paiza_Golden_Horde.jpg">https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Paiza_Golden_Horde.jpg</a>.<br></div><div class="csl-bib-body" style="line-height: 1.35; margin-left: 2em; text-indent: -2em;"><div class="csl-entry" style="margin-bottom: 1em;"><br></div><div class="csl-entry" style="margin-bottom: 1em;">Metropolitan Museum of Art. “Paiza (Imperial Pass) Artifact, 13th Century. MET.” <a href="https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/39624">https://www.metmuseum.org/art/collection/search/39624</a>.<br></div><div class="csl-entry" style="margin-bottom: 1em;">MÜNKÜYEV, N. TS. “A NEW MONGOLIAN P’AI-TZŬ FROM SIMFEROPOL.” <i>Acta Orientalia Academiae Scientiarum Hungaricae</i> 31, no. 2 (1977): 185–215. <a href="http://www.jstor.org/stable/23682673">http://www.jstor.org/stable/23682673</a>.<br></div><div class="csl-entry">Printables.Com. “Rectangular Paiza by Halodine | Download Free STL Model.” Accessed May 4, 2026. <a href="https://www.printables.com/model/1199312-rectangular-paiza">https://www.printables.com/model/1199312-rectangular-paiza</a>.<br></div></div><div><br></div>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>35.0880969</longitude>
				<latitude>32.916975</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>0</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<gx:fovy>35</gx:fovy>
				<range>19514.91242582565</range>
				<altitudeMode>relativeToGround</altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#__managed_style_4A5A4B72FE3F6294FB44</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<altitudeMode>relativeToGround</altitudeMode>
				<coordinates>35.08040752209105,32.93502867587649,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="02B4F080C83F2C0C8CF4">
			<name>Ayas/ Yumurtalık</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<bettercanvas-portal style="overflow: visible; position: relative; width: 0px; height: 0px; display: block;"></bettercanvas-portal><div><span style="overflow: visible; position: relative; width: 0px; height: 0px; display: block;"></span><br></div><div>Port of lesser Armenia, the dock by which the Polos begin the journey eastward from acre after conferring with Pope Gregory X ( Marco Polo and R. E. Latham, <i>The Travels of Marco Polo</i>, Repr, Penguin Classics Harmondsworth [etc.]: Penguin, 1978, 37–39.)<br></div>]]></description>
