		<Placemark id="0E7AA7E17A3F24C35D5B">
			<name>Alamut Castle</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<bettercanvas-portal style="overflow: visible; position: relative; width: 0px; height: 0px; display: block;"></bettercanvas-portal><div><span style="overflow: visible; position: relative; width: 0px; height: 0px; display: block;"></span><br></div><div><span style="overflow: visible; position: relative; width: 0px; height: 0px; display: block;"></span><br></div><div>The primary stronghold of the Nizari Assassins, captured by Hulagu Khan after a 3-year siege in 1256 (1262 according to Polo). Likely not visited directly by Polo, according to some scholars, but alluded to on the journey east from Hormuz. (Polo and Latham, <i>The Travels of Marco Polo</i>. 73.)<br></div><div><br></div><div>Gunpowder-loaded ballista artillery was reportedly used in the Mongol siege of Alamut, a landmark for its employment this far west made possible by the technological movement of the Mongol Silk Road, forever enshrined within the assassin myth (Dashdondog, “Mongol Diplomacy of the Alamut Period.” 321)<br></div><div><br></div><div><br></div><div class="csl-bib-body" style="line-height: 1.35; margin-left: 2em; text-indent: -2em;"><div class="csl-entry" style="margin-bottom: 1em;">Dashdondog, Bayarsaikhan. “Mongol Diplomacy of the Alamut Period.” <i>Eurasian Studies</i> 17, no. 2 (2020): 310–26. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1163/24685623-12340078">https://doi.org/10.1163/24685623-12340078</a>.<br></div><div class="csl-entry" style="margin-bottom: 1em;">Haw, Stephen G. “The Mongol Empire – the First ‘Gunpowder Empire’?” <i>Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society</i> 23, no. 3 (2013): 441–69. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1017/S1356186313000369">https://doi.org/10.1017/S1356186313000369</a>.<br></div><div class="csl-entry" style="margin-bottom: 1em;">Istanbul University, and Anıl Yasin Oğuz. “An Enquiry into Gunpowder Weapons Used by Hülegü in the Middle East Campaign.” <i>GOLDEN HORDE REVIEW</i> 11, no. 4 (2023): 728–41. <a href="https://doi.org/10.22378/2313-6197.2023-11-4.728-741">https://doi.org/10.22378/2313-6197.2023-11-4.728-741</a>.<br></div><div class="csl-entry" style="margin-bottom: 1em;">MIR-AHMADI, MARYAM. “MARCO POLO IN IRAN.” <i>Oriente Moderno</i> 88 (2008): 1–13. <a href="http://www.jstor.org/stable/23073478">http://www.jstor.org/stable/23073478</a>.<br></div><div class="csl-entry" style="margin-bottom: 1em;">Raphael, Kate. “Mongol Siege Warfare on the Banks of the Euphrates and the Question of Gunpowder (1260–1312).” <i>Journal of the Royal Asiatic Society</i> 19, no. 3 (2009): 355–70. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1017/S1356186309009717">https://doi.org/10.1017/S1356186309009717</a>.<br></div><div class="csl-entry" style="margin-bottom: 1em;">Sparavigna, Amelia Carolina. “Marco Polo in Persia.” <i>SSRN Electronic Journal</i>, ahead of print, 2020. <a href="https://doi.org/10.2139/ssrn.3674354">https://doi.org/10.2139/ssrn.3674354</a>.<br></div><div class="csl-entry">Virani, Shafique N. “An Old Man, a Garden, and an Assembly of Assassins: Legends and Realities of the Nizari Ismaili Muslims.” <i>Iran</i> 61, no. 2 (2023): 272–84. <a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/05786967.2021.1901062">https://doi.org/10.1080/05786967.2021.1901062</a>.<br></div></div><div><br></div>]]></description>
