			<Point>
				<coordinates>74.85586239446003,33.97141224507821,1876.824517978505</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="022E6E2FC13F3AD41BE3">
			<name>Karakorum</name>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>102.8477778</longitude>
				<latitude>47.2102778</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>0</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<gx:fovy>35</gx:fovy>
				<range>690.1264051815299</range>
				<altitudeMode>relativeToGround</altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#__managed_style_07231ADBB53F6294FB3F</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<extrude>1</extrude>
				<coordinates>102.8477778,47.2102778,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="0F8F98D0853F43B1335C">
			<name>Masyaf</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<bettercanvas-portal style="overflow: visible; position: relative; width: 0px; height: 0px; display: block;"></bettercanvas-portal><div>A village formerly housing a fortress stronghold for the Nizari Ismaril Assassins branch in Syria, though not directly visited or mentioned, it is alluded to. (Polo and Latham, <i>The Travels of Marco Polo</i>, 73). <br></div><div><br></div><div>It is notable for showing the extent of the practical reach of the assassins into the political realm of Syria, while also expanding on the mythology of the assassins in popular culture.<br></div><div><br></div><div class="csl-bib-body" style="line-height: 1.35; margin-left: 2em; text-indent: -2em;"><div class="csl-entry">Heng, Geraldine. “Sex, Lies, and Paradise: The Assassins, Prester John, and the Fabulation of Civilizational Identities.” <i>Differences</i> 23, no. 1 (May 1, 2012): 1–31. doi:<a href="https://doi.org/10.1215/10407391-1533511">10.1215/10407391-1533511</a>.<br></div><div class="csl-entry"><br></div><div class="csl-entry">Polo, Marco, and R. E. Latham. <i>The Travels of Marco Polo</i>. Repr. Penguin Classics. Harmondsworth [etc.]: Penguin, 1978.<br></div></div><div><br></div>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>36.34306805</longitude>
				<latitude>35.06450785</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>0</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<gx:fovy>35</gx:fovy>
				<range>4402.166706691582</range>
				<altitudeMode>relativeToGround</altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#__managed_style_1E3DE2C9413F6294FB40</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<altitudeMode>relativeToGround</altitudeMode>
				<coordinates>36.3382086,35.0623329,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="0073FA3C8E3F34665027">
			<name>Herat/ Approximate region of &apos;The Dry Tree&apos;</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div><span style="overflow: visible; position: relative; width: 0px; height: 0px; display: block;"></span><br></div><div>The site of a battle between Arghun and Barak Khan "in the region of the dry tree" , in notes attributed to Herat (Polo and Latham, <i>The Travels of Marco Polo</i>, 69, 319).<br></div><div><br></div><div>While scholarly sources are scant, this also connects to the wider medieval legend of a 'dry tree' which resided in the desert 'at the edge of the world' according to medieval Europeans.<br></div>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>62.21107005</longitude>
				<latitude>34.353456</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>0</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<gx:fovy>35</gx:fovy>
