		<Placemark id="0B6D149AB03F2F6539E0">
			<name>Assssssin fortress/ Qal’ eh Kuh of Ferdows</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<div><span style="overflow: visible; position: relative; width: 0px; height: 0px; display: block;"></span><br></div><div>Location of a ruined assassin fortress. The assassins are referred to at this point in the journey eastward from Hormuz, even though the specific fortress named is much further west (Marco Polo and R. E. Latham, <i>The Travels of Marco Polo</i>, Repr, Penguin Classics Harmondsworth [etc.], 1978, 70.)<br></div><div><br></div><div>This mention may be extrapolated as Polo passing by an additional ruined assassin stronghold between Kuhbanan and Sheberghan to fill this largest gap in the overland route. (Amelia Carolina Sparavigna, “Marco Polo in Persia,” <i>SSRN Electronic Journal</i>, 2020, 3, doi:<a href="https://doi.org/10.2139/ssrn.3674354">10.2139/ssrn.3674354</a>.)<br></div><div><br></div><div><div>Polo, Marco, and R. E. Latham. <i>The Travels of Marco Polo</i>. Repr. Penguin Classics. Harmondsworth [etc.]: Penguin, 1978.<br></div><div>Sparavigna, Amelia Carolina. “Marco Polo in Persia.” <i>SSRN Electronic Journal</i>, 2020. doi:<a href="https://doi.org/10.2139/ssrn.3674354">10.2139/ssrn.3674354</a>.<br></div><div>Virani, Shafique N. “An Old Man, a Garden, and an Assembly of Assassins: Legends and Realities of the Nizari Ismaili Muslims.” <i>Iran</i> 61, no. 2 (July 3, 2023): 272–84. doi:<a href="https://doi.org/10.1080/05786967.2021.1901062">10.1080/05786967.2021.1901062</a>.<br></div></div><div><br></div><div><br></div>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>58.136</longitude>
				<latitude>33.9098</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>0</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<gx:fovy>35</gx:fovy>
				<range>2090.195410715397</range>
				<altitudeMode>relativeToGround</altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#__managed_style_1E3DE2C9413F6294FB40</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<extrude>1</extrude>
				<coordinates>58.13586202656653,33.91175865891833,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="083F58C5173F49D00920">
			<name>Mount Ararat</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<bettercanvas-portal style="overflow: visible; position: relative; width: 0px; height: 0px; display: block;"></bettercanvas-portal><div>'In the heart of greater Armenia is a very high mountain shaped like a cube (or cup) on which Noah's Ark is said to have rested, whence it is called the mountain of Noah's Ark.' (Polo and Latham, <i>The Travels of Marco Polo</i>, 48).<br></div><div><br></div><div class="csl-bib-body" style="line-height: 1.35; margin-left: 2em; text-indent: -2em;"><div class="csl-entry">Polo, Marco, and R. E. Latham. <i>The Travels of Marco Polo</i>. Repr. Penguin Classics. Harmondsworth [etc.]: Penguin, 1978.<br></div></div><div><br></div>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>44.2990761</longitude>
