		<Placemark id="073DD67B8B3F2550DEF8">
			<name>Dadu/ Cambulac</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<bettercanvas-portal style="overflow: visible; position: relative; width: 0px; height: 0px; display: block;"></bettercanvas-portal><div><span style="overflow: visible; position: relative; width: 0px; height: 0px; display: block;"></span><br></div><div>The Yuan walled administrative capital with a palace district, as well as the Yuan reserve and paper currency mint, enforced by imperial authority and backed by silver (Polo and Latham, <i>The Travels of Marco Polo</i>, 147).<br></div><div><br></div><div>Here, the use of printing within china had been extant for the use of paper money but the mongols would begin to enforce this system under legal penalty (Polo and Latham, <i>The Travels of Marco Polo</i>, 149). <br></div><div><br></div><div>Eventually, this format of currency would spread the world over with stronger state economic structures, to the present day, where it is the standard.<br></div><div><br></div><div class="csl-bib-body" style="line-height: 1.35; margin-left: 2em; text-indent: -2em;"><div class="csl-entry" style="margin-bottom: 1em;">Carter, Thomas Francis. <i>The Invention of Printing in China and Its Spread Westward</i>. With Princeton Theological Seminary Library. New York : Columbia University Press, 1925. <a href="http://archive.org/details/inventionofprint00cart_0">http://archive.org/details/inventionofprint00cart_0</a>.<br></div><div class="csl-entry" style="margin-bottom: 1em;">Goodrich, L. Carrington. “A BRONZE BLOCK FOR THE PRINTING OF CHINESE PAPER CURRENCY (ca. 1287).” <i>Museum Notes (American Numismatic Society)</i> 4 (1950): 127–30. <a href="http://www.jstor.org/stable/43573321">http://www.jstor.org/stable/43573321</a>.<br></div><div class="csl-entry" style="margin-bottom: 1em;">PHGCOM. <i>English:&nbsp; Yuan Dynasty Banknote with Its Printing Wood Plate 1287. An Upper Line Reads: 「至元通行寳鈔」 Zhì Yuán Tōng Háng Bǎo Chā (Pinyin&nbsp; Left Line: ’Phags-Pa Script) Reads: Zhì Yuán Bǎo Chāo&nbsp;: To Say 「至元寳鈔」. The Smaller Chinese Characters in the Bottom Half of the Note Say "(This Note) Can Be Circulated in Various Provinces without Expiration Dates. Counterfeiters Would Be Put to Death.</i> 2007. Own work, photographed at Tokyo Currency Museum. <a href="https://commons.wikimedia.org/w/index.php?title=File:Yuan_dynasty_banknote_with_its_printing_plate_1287.jpg&amp;oldid=1184644244">https://commons.wikimedia.org/w/index.php?title=File:Yuan_dynasty_banknote_with_its_printing_plate_1287.jpg&amp;oldid=1184644244</a>.<br></div><div class="csl-entry">Williamson, Alayna. “Technological Developments in the Mongol Empire.” <i>Science Technology and Society a Student Led Exploration</i>, July 29, 2020. <a href="https://opentextbooks.clemson.edu/sciencetechnologyandsociety/chapter/technological-developments-in-the-mongol-empire/">https://opentextbooks.clemson.edu/sciencetechnologyandsociety/chapter/technological-developments-in-the-mongol-empire/</a>.<br></div></div><div><br></div>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>116.4277506</longitude>
				<latitude>39.9755829</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
