			</Point>
		</Placemark>
		<Placemark id="09289867033F4462ABF0">
			<name>Siang-Yang-fu/Xiangyang</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<bettercanvas-portal style="overflow: visible; position: relative; width: 0px; height: 0px; display: block;"></bettercanvas-portal><div><span style="overflow: visible; position: relative; width: 0px; height: 0px; display: block;"></span><br></div><div>Famous for Polo's supposed introduction of counterweight trebuchets to the Mongol army at the battle of Xiangyang, used to break its walls. (Marco Polo and R. E. Latham, <i>The Travels of Marco Polo</i>, Repr, Penguin Classics (Harmondsworth [etc.]: Penguin, 1978), 207.)<br></div><div><br></div><div>The counterweight trebuchet first appeared in Europe (Italy) as early as the siege of Castelnuovo Bocca d'Adda in 1199, although it may have been used earlier during the Crusades. (Chevedden, “The Invention of the Counterweight Trebuchet.” 76.)<br></div><div><br></div><div class="csl-bib-body" style="line-height: 1.35; margin-left: 2em; text-indent: -2em;"><div class="csl-entry" style="margin-bottom: 1em;">Chevedden, Paul E. “The Invention of the Counterweight Trebuchet: A Study in Cultural Diffusion.” <i>Dumbarton Oaks Papers</i> 54 (2000): 71. <a href="https://doi.org/10.2307/1291833">https://doi.org/10.2307/1291833</a>.<br></div><div class="csl-entry" style="margin-bottom: 1em;">Chevedden, Paul E., Les Eigenbrod, Vernard Foley, and Werner Soedel. “The Trebuchet.” <i>Scientific American</i> 273, no. 1 (1995): 66–71. <a href="http://www.jstor.org/stable/24981453">http://www.jstor.org/stable/24981453</a>.<br></div><div class="csl-entry" style="margin-bottom: 1em;">GRAFF, DAVID A. “China, Byzantium, and the Shadow of the Steppe.” <i>Dumbarton Oaks Papers</i> 65/66 (2011): 157–68. <a href="http://www.jstor.org/stable/41933707">http://www.jstor.org/stable/41933707</a>.<br></div><div class="csl-entry">Rachewiltz, Igor de. <i>In the Service of the Khan: Eminent Personalities of the Early Mongol-Yüan Period (1200-1300)</i>. Otto Harrassowitz Verlag, 1993.<br></div></div><div><br></div>]]></description>
