		<Placemark id="0442F9848D3F43DABC90">
			<name>Sri Pada / Adam&apos;s Peak</name>
			<description><![CDATA[<bettercanvas-portal style="overflow: visible; position: relative; width: 0px; height: 0px; display: block;"></bettercanvas-portal><div><span style="overflow: visible; position: relative; width: 0px; height: 0px; display: block;"></span><br></div><div>This location, according to Polo, is recorded as "Sakyamuni Burkhan", attributed to the Buddha while also noting it is considered the grave of adam among 'Saracen'( likely muslim and eastern christian) (Polo and Latham, <i>The Travels of Marco Polo</i>, 281).<br></div><div><br></div><div>This attribution to several religions regarding a geographic marker is a clear example of syncretism, even on a local/folkloric scale. This further highlights the legend-laden worldview of Polo and Co.&nbsp;</div>]]></description>
			<LookAt>
				<longitude>80.4993882</longitude>
				<latitude>6.80964285</latitude>
				<altitude>0</altitude>
				<heading>0</heading>
				<tilt>0</tilt>
				<gx:fovy>35</gx:fovy>
				<range>5691.379664274233</range>
				<altitudeMode>relativeToGround</altitudeMode>
			</LookAt>
			<styleUrl>#__managed_style_219AB365DA3F6294FB44</styleUrl>
			<Point>
				<altitudeMode>relativeToGround</altitudeMode>
				<coordinates>80.4993882,6.809643,0</coordinates>
			</Point>
		</Placemark>
